<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880602-0140 </DOCNO><HL> Kidder Peabody Is Chosen To Advise Israel on Debt </HL><SO> </SO><CO> GE MDEST GOVMT </CO><IN> MON BNK </IN><DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Israel appointed Kidder, Peabody andamp; Co. as adviser for the refinancing of as much as $5.5 billion of its U.S. foreign military sales debt.    This is part of a refinancing program of about $15 billion offered by the U.S. government to foreign countries with foreign military sales debt that carries an interest rate of 10% of more. These loans were made by the U.S. to allow countries -- including Israel, Egypt, Turkey, Pakistan and Morocco -- to buy defense articles and services.    As financial adviser, Kidder, a unit of General Electric Co., will counsel on selecting an underwriting team for the refinancing, take part in the structure and pricing of all transactions, and assist in contacts with U.S. government agencies, including the Treasury, the Defense Department and the Office of Management and Budget. </TEXT></DOC>